Vehicles | Reference.com









































www.reference.com
































Vehicles




Q:

What is the Large Hadron Collider?



A:
The Large Hadron Collider is a particle accelerator and is the largest of its type in the world. It is used for conducting experiments in theoretical physics and was built with a focus on determining whether the Higgs boson particle exists. 


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters




























Airplanes & Helicopters









Q:
How many airplanes are there in the world?


A:
There are about 20,000 airplanes in the world as of 2013. Aircraft maker Boeing projects demand for new airplanes to top 35,000 over the next 20 years. The new planes are expected to meet rising demand and to replace older, less efficient models.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters












Q:
Can passengers take a razor on a plane?


A:
Rules regarding packing razors in airplane luggage depend on the type of razor in question. Disposable razors and cartridges are allowed in carry-on bags, while most other types of razor must be secured in a checked bag.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters












Q:
What is the most common cause of plane crashes?


A:
The most common cause of airplane crashes is human error. According to the BBC, up to 50 percent of all airline accidents can be attributed to pilot error, but the Baltic Aviation Academy suggests that the number may be as high as 70 percent. Frequent factors that contribute to human error resulting in a crash include striking wires, losing control of the plane or flying into the water or land.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters












Q:
What is the average speed of a helicopter?


A:
A two-seat trainer helicopter averages flight speeds between 90 and 105 mph. A five-seat turbine helicopter can reach average cruising speeds between 130 and 145 mph. The maximum speed in some helicopters is about 255 mph.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters












Q:
How do stunt planes produce smoke?


A:
The smoke trails emitted from stunt or acrobatic planes are usually the result of injecting oil or diesel fuel into the exhaust. Often, coloring is also injected for effect.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters












Q:
How much is a helicopter?


A:
The actual cost of a helicopter varies depending on many factors, including age, size and available features on a particular unit. As of 2014, basic helicopters typically start around $120,000 for a two-seat pre-owned unit, and can escalate to several million dollars for the large commercial or luxury models.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Airplanes & Helicopters








See More Airplanes & Helicopters Questions









Buying & Selling









Q:
What are the dimensions of a school bus?


A:
A school bus would typically be about 9.5 to 11 feet high and around 8 feet wide. The length of a school bus can range from about 12 feet to 40 feet.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Buying & Selling












Q:
What is a good mileage for a used car?


A:
According to Samarins.com, a good mileage figure for a used car is 155,000 or less. While low mileage is desirable in a used car, it is not a guarantee that a vehicle is in reasonably good shape for its age.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Buying & Selling












Q:
Is craigslist reliable for used cars?


A:
Craigslist can be a great place to buy a reliable used car if you are careful and do your research before you answer any ads.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Buying & Selling












Q:
How much did a new car cost in 1933?


A:
According to the website TheCostOfLiving.com, the average car cost $605 in 1933. Because of inflation, however, a dollar was worth far more in 1933 than it is today, so the cost was roughly equivalent to $10,214 in 2010 dollars.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Buying & Selling












Q:
How do you get cash for junk cars?


A:
Several businesses pay cash for junk cars, including Pick-n-Pull and US Junk Cars. Both vendors arrange a deal with the seller. Then, they either pick up the car or wait for the seller to drop it off.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Buying & Selling












Q:
What is the fair market value of my car?


A:
The fair market value of a car can be determined based on the year, make, model, mileage and condition of the vehicle. The car's history can also greatly alter its fair market value. The Kelley Blue Book is a great resource for accurately determining your car's fair market value.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Buying & Selling








See More Buying & Selling Questions









Car Makes & Models









Q:
Who makes Volvo cars?


A:
Volvo Car Corporation is a Swedish premium automobile manufacturer headquartered in Gothenburg, Sweden. As of 2014, Zhejiang Geely Holding Group of China owns the company.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Car Makes & Models












Q:
What does "EML" mean on a BMW?


A:
As with many cars, the EML on a BMW is the engine management light. When the engine management light shows on a dashboard, it means the computers aboard the car have detected a problem with the engine.


See Full Answer

Filed Under:


Car Makes & Models












Q:
What are some of the best cars for college students?


A:
Money Crashers lists the best cars for college students as the Nissan Versa, Hyundai Accent, Smart ForTwo, Chevrolet Aveo, Kia Rio and Toyota Yaris. Other cars on the list include the Kia Soul, Suzuki SX4, Hyundai Elantra and Kia Forte. The cars were chosen for their affordability, reliability and sensibility.


See Full Answer

